      <scopecontent id="aspace_f11cce71af813c0cae441e88b8ca60b0">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The Aaron Columbus Burr (circa 1808-1882) Papers, 1838-1871, consist of correspondence and business relating to an attempt by Aaron Columbus Burr and James Grant to purchase a tract of land known as Stand Creek in British Honduras. After purchasing this land they planned to sell it to the United States in the hope that it would be used for colonizing freed American blacks. When this scheme failed, the American Honduras Company was formed to cut and export mahogany.</p>
         <p>The correspondence is concerned mainly with the attempt to establish a colony in British Honduras. Notable correspondents include Hamilton Fish, James Grant, and Anna Ella Carroll. Among the business papers are the proposal for the founding of a colony for freed American slaves, descriptions of the lands in British Honduras, and documents relating to the mahogany industry.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
  
